Next came authentication principles which break down how a user and the business is kept secure throughout the duration of their session. Each user will have their own account equipped with username and password that will also have extra secure features that include special keys and secure questions that only the user should know the answer to. Once they are in the system each user will have their own level of functionality within the system. For example will have access to a lot more controls than a standard employee would. This adds to the level of security so standard employees do not have free reign of a possible security risk. There are many ways in which a user can authenticate themselves to enter the system. They could use PIN or password along with a username which is unique to them if it was to enter a computerised system or if it was another type of system then the best thing to use may be biometrics which can use finger prints, voice prints, retina scans or even palm prints. \
